      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### **Hg²⁺ has by far the highest affinity**, with log K₁ = 9.64 — nearly **8 orders of magnitude** greater than Cd²⁺.\n\n### Chemistry Insight\n\nThis result is a textbook illustration of **HSAB (Hard-Soft Acid-Base) theory**. Thiocyanate (SCN⁻) is a soft/borderline base that coordinates through its sulfur atom to soft metals. Among these three d-block metals, Hg²⁺ is the *softest* acid (large, polarizable, d¹⁰ configuration), which explains its extraordinarily strong affinity for the soft sulfur donor. Cd²⁺ is borderline-soft and Pb²⁺ is borderline, consistent with their progressively weaker binding. The large exothermic ΔH for Hg²⁺–SCN⁻ (−49 kJ/mol) compared to Cd²⁺ (−13 kJ/mol) and Pb²⁺ (−1.3 kJ/mol) further underscores the dominant covalent character of the Hg–S bond.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
